    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so when people talk about \"judicial overreach\" in this context, is that a legitimate legal critique based on constitutional principles, or is it just a political way for people to complain when they don't like a ruling? like, is there a real scholarly basis for saying the court is acting outside its authority, or is that just rhetoric?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Judicial overreach\" is a legitimate legal critique when an actor believes a court has exceeded its constitutional mandate, such as by legislating from the bench rather than interpreting law. In the context of the Second Amendment, critics argue the Court is overreaching when it appears to impose a broad, modern right that they claim the Framers never intended. However, this critique is often heavily colored by the political disagreement over the very nature of constitutional interpretation itself.",
      "source": "target",
